The paper discusses the "digital Michelangelo project," which was a computer vision project that involved multiple people from diverse fields and pushed the capabilities of acquisition systems. The paper reflects on several issues relevant to the field of computer vision and research in general, going beyond the technical aspects of the work. Given the focus on computer vision and the interdisciplinary nature of the project, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. However, the project also involved graphics (cs.GR), human-computer interaction (cs.HC), multimedia (cs.MM), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) aspects, making these sub-categories also likely.
